Output 6

The “data()” function is used to get a list of all the in-built datasets present in R. I chose the dataset “airquality”, which consist of the daily readings of 4 air quality values (Ozone, Solar, Wind, Temp) in New York, from May to September 1973. The “head()” function returns the first 10 rows of the dataset. To learn more about the attributes and definitions of the selected datatset, I’ve used the “help()” function.

Analysis 1: The summary() function is used to generate a summary of the variables in this dataset, including mean, median, min, max, and quartiles. Analysis 2: The ggplot() function is used to create a scatterplot, with Ozone on the x-axis and Solar Radiations on the y-axis, to observe the distribution of the data points and identify outliers. Analysis 3: The hist() function is used to create an histogram of the numerical variable Temp, to display the frequency of the datapoints within bins/intervals. Analysis 4: The cor() function is used to find the correlations between all the variables. From the output, it is observed that the correlation between Wind and Ozone is maximum and positive; it is also observed that the correlation between Temp and Ozone is maximum and negative. Analysis 5: Omitted the NA values, and created a kmeans model to perform clustering of the data. Then, used fviz_cluster to plot the clustering.

Conclusion

  1. I learnt to use the “getwd()” function to get my current working directory. I used the “class()” function to find the class of a variable.
  2. I learnt to create a vector and perform a few operations on the vector, like finding the length, retrieving an element from it, etc. I also learnt to create a matrix and combine matrices using “rbind()” and “cbind()” functions.
  3. Further, I learnt to work with in-built datasets in R-Studio. I performed different types of analyses on the “airquality” dataset. I summarized the dataset which produced the mean, median, min, max, and quartile values of each column in the dataset. I worked with scatterplots and histograms to observe the distribution of data points and explore relationships between different variables of the dataset.
  4. Using the abovementioned dataset, I also worked with the “cor()” function to find the correlation between different variables. Moreover, I learnt to create a kmeans model to perform clustering of data, and then plotted the clusters using “fviz_cluster()” function.
